Nov 18 2009 	Very nice hotel	We arrived mid afternoon after a very long flight and were greeted by a very friendly receptionist. Another member of staff (I got the impression it may even have been the owner) chatted with us and told us about the facilities. On hearing of the kettle I mentioned that, being typical Brits, we would love a cup of tea. He immediately went off to fetch a selection of teabags and bottled water for us, and couldn't have been more helpful or friendly.The room was lovely - maybe not as large or filled with every convenience as some hotels, but it felt like someone's home. The free cheese and wine buffet looked very nice, but the jet lag caught up with us by late afternoon so we didn't take part. Breakfast was great - toast, tea,coffee, cereal yoghurts etc.On our final night we were called by reception asking if we needed a taxi for departure - we had actually booked a hire car so didn't require one- but it was a nice touch.Location couldn't be better - right on Union Square. The only complaint whatsoever was that a loud air conditioner seemed to start just outside our window at about 4-5 am both mornings. As we left we mentioned this - seems it belongs to the Steakhouse next door and they are not supposed to start up until much later. The receptionist actually thanked us for bringing it to his attention, and promised that they would look into this. Such was the my positive impression of this lovely hotel, that I genuinely believed that they would do this.	
Nov 17 2009 	good small hotel 	To be honest, our first impression was not very positive since this hotel looked a little bit shabbily small with only one door at the entrance where only one receptionist attending the guests. However, we finally realized that such facts did not matter at all. As its name suggests, the hotel is just thirty seconds a pied from the Union Square, the heart of the city within walking distance to Chinatown, Nob Hill and Financial District, etc. The hotel offers breakfast and a happy-hour reception (free californiia wine!!) at a tiny southmost spot on the 3rd and 5th floors, where any guests can enjoy frank conversations with others.Overall, we highly recommend this hotel to all who like a small hotel in the heart of a big city except for those who do not prefer much to share a breakfast and/or happy-hour table with other unknown guests (well, you can also take the food and drink to your room or a respective spot on other floors).	
