Jun 20 2008 	Great Location!	I went to San Francisco in June on business and since I book short notice all the chain hotels were really expensive. I searched for boutique hotels and found The Inn at Union Square with a great rate less than half of the big guys. Being a little wary of unknown hotels I always rely on Trip Advisor to help me make decisions and this time was no exception. The reviews were all fantastic and for good reason. This is a really nice hotel with great staff. It's a little old but that adds to the charm especially in San Francisco. You can hear the cable car bells running down Powell Street which you are literally only steps from. I couldn't believe how close it is to Union Square. You are also only a few blocks from Nob Hill and China Town (five minute walk). Bed was comfortable, there is a business center, wine and cheese every evening and a decent continental breakfast with real pastries every morning (not the Courtyard buffet junk - if you are a frquent traveler you know what I mean). Turndown service is a nice touch too. The staff were all very friendly and David at the front desk was really helpful in helping me select a restaurant. Parking is a little step if you vallet but the Union Square garage is only a block away.They are located right next to the JW Marriot and across the street from the Westin St. Francis and I just smiled to myself that I was staying in this great little hotel, enjoying the same location and paying less than half the price of those guys.	
Jun 18 2008 	Great Location Incredible Amenities	My husband and I visited San Fran for five nights in early June with my in-laws. I was appointed &quot;hotel finder.&quot; After reading countless positive reviews and finding an outstanding rate for this hotel on their website, I confidently booked two rooms.Our stay was perfect in every way, and I won't go into all the details because the amenities are described in almost every review here, but please know that we all agreed this was one of our all time favorite places to stay. Right off the trolley line and union square, breakfast and snacks included, ROBES in the room, friendly &amp; helpful staff, and extremely comfortable rooms. I read on a few reviews about the rooms being small, but I have to disagree with this. We stayed in a regular king, and there was more than enough room. A side table with two chairs on one side, and a desk/vanity on the other side. The bathroom is a good size, not massive, but I have stayed in places with much smaller. No AC, but had a ceiling fan and opened our window. Our view was a brick wall, but we didn't mind because our room was quiet as can be.I love staying at hotels, it is always a thrill for me, and I have stayed in a lot of hotels. This place goes on the top of my list, seriously. I'm sure you could stay at a very fancy/expensive hotel and love it, but why not spend the bulk of your money on meals, shows and shopping? This place has incredible value, without short changing you on amenities or comfort.	
Jun 9 2008 	Loved Inn at Union Square	We found the Inn at Union Square in San Francisco very charming, a small scale hotel with lots of service and suggestions from the very friendly front desk concierges. The rooms were small, but very comfortable and clean and provided well with a nice size flat screen TV and other usual expected hotel equipment. The only snag I experienced there was that my phone was not working initially and after being serviced, I never received the hand-set, but got by using speaker phone.Loved the extensive complementary breakfast set ups in the kitchen/sitting areas at the end of each floor, and the wine and cheese presentation from 5:30 p.m. until 7:00 p.m. was a nice way to get to know other hotel occupants and experience some good wine and snacks--a little briefing to what we experienced on the second leg of our trip, Napa and Sonoma Valley for wine tasting!Great suggestions from the front desk personnel on places to go, eat and see. The hotel is so centrally located, we were within walking distance to most attractions: Fisherman's Wharf, San Francisco Center Shopping Mall, Chinatown, and great restaurants with diverse ethnic cuisines. We walked around the corner from the hotel one night to take in some good blues at a club called Biscuits and Blues. The last night of our stay, we took a short walk to a lovely French restaurant called Cafe Claude. It was the favorite of our stay in San Francisco--cozy French ambiance with an especially informative wine educator, who gave a lengthy list of suggestions for our visit to Napa.My highest compliments go out to Inn at Union Square and I would enjoy another stay there unquestionably.	
